    {
      "role": "tool",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "tool-result",
          "toolCallId": "toolu_01Kmej7uKHNWCLkneiFUgyXa",
          "toolName": "get_wiring_guide",
          "output": {
            "type": "json",
            "value": {
              "guide": "## Wiring Rules\n- ALL connections come from WIRES, not pin assignments. Set all component pins to null.\n- Same-row cols 0-4 are connected (left bus). Same-row cols 5-9 are connected (right bus). No wire needed within a bus.\n- Use ONE direct wire per Arduino pin. If a net fans out (multiple loads), land one wire on a breadboard row/rail and branch from there.\n- LED: always add 220Ω resistor. Use ledResistorPairs in propose_circuit — auto-wires cathode→resistor→GND.\n- **Series resistors** (7-segment, etc.): Use throughComponent in propose_circuit wires. Example: {arduinoPin:2, toComponent:0, toPin:\"a\", throughComponent:1, throughEntryPin:\"b\", throughExitPin:\"a\"}. The tool auto-places the resistor on the same row as the target pin.\n- 3-pin components (servo/pot/sensor): each pin on a SEPARATE ROW or they short via bus. Wire signal→(row,x), 5V→(row+1,x), GND→(row+2,x).\n- Button: straddles center gap. Pin \"a\" at col 3, pin \"b\" at col 6. Wire signal to one side, GND/5V to the other.\n- High-current loads (servo, motor, relay) should use external power_supply with common ground.\n- For shared GND or shared power, prefer rail distribution: Arduino GND/5V → rail once, then rail → each component.\n- Resistor: always at cols 3 (pin a) and 6 (pin b), bridging the center gap. Placement col is ignored.\n\n## Footprints\nLED: 2 rows vertical (anode y, cathode y+1) | Resistor: horizontal at cols 3,6 (a=col3, b=col6) | Button: cols 3,6 rows y,y+1 (a=col3, b=col6) | Servo/Pot: 3 rows | 7-seg: 9 rows (a-g,dp,gnd) | Capacitor: 2 rows\n\n## Pin Names\nLED: anode,cathode | RGB: red,green,blue,common | Button: a,b | Resistor: a,b | Capacitor: positive,negative | Pot: vcc,signal,gnd | Buzzer: positive,negative | Servo: signal,vcc,gnd | NeoPixel: din,vcc,gnd | PIR/DHT/IR: signal | Relay/Motor: signal | ShiftReg: data,clock,latch | OLED: gnd,vcc,scl,sda | LCD: vss,vdd,vo,rs,rw,en,d4,d5,d6,d7,a,k | 7seg: a,b,c,d,e,f,g,dp,gnd\n\n## Arduino Pins\nBoard target: arduino_uno\nSignal pin IDs: 0-69 (board-dependent)\nAnalog pins: A0=14, A1=15, A2=16, A3=17, A4=18, A5=19\nPWM pins: D3,D5,D6,D9,D10,D11\nSpecial wire pin IDs: 5V=-1, 3V3=-2, GND=-3/-4/-6, VIN=-5, AREF=-7"
            }
          },
          "providerOptions": {
            "anthropic": {
              "caller": {
                "type": "direct"
              }
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Now I have all the info I need. The resistor pin **b** is at **col 6** (right bus), and the seven segment is at **row 16, col 3**. Each segment pin maps to a row offset. Let me check the exact seven segment pin rows and connect everything.\n\nThe seven segment occupies 9 rows starting at y=16: pins a→row16, b→row17, c→row18, d→row19, e→row20, f→row21, g→row22, dp→row23, gnd→row24.\n\nResistors are at rows 7–13 (R_A=7, R_B=8, R_C=9, R_D=10, R_E=11, R_F=12, R_G=13), each with pin **b** at **col 6**. The seven segment segment pins are on the **left bus (col 3)** of their respective rows.\n\nI'll now connect all 7 resistor-b → segment pins, then wire GND:"
